en's school uniforms to taking night classes; from obtaining first-ever bank loans to installing running water. Sewing Hope invites readers into the apparel industry's sweatshops and the Alta Gracia factory to learn how the anti-sweatshop started, how it overcame challenges, and how the impact of its business model could transform the global industry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aClothing tradexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aSocial responsibility of business. 0aSweatshops. 4aalta gracia factory. 4aanti-sweatshop. 4aapparel industry sweatshops. 4adominican republic. 4afactory fires. 4ahigh safety standards. 4ahuman rights advocate. 4ahuman rights. 4aindependent monitor. 4alegitimate union. 4aliving wage. 4apolitical activism. 4asafety standards. 4asocial activist. 4aworkers rights. 4aworking conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Labor.2bisacsh1 aKline, John M., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520966246423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520966246.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles